@page "/semantic-buttons"
<PageTitle>Semantic Buttons - Saascade Docs</PageTitle>

<h1 id="semantic-buttons">Semantic Buttons</h1>

<div class="doc-layout">

<main class="documentation">

    <TechCard>
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">
                Saascade provides semantic button aliases that convey intent
                and apply appropriate design-system styling automatically.
            </p>

            <hr />

            <h3>AcceptButton</h3>
            <pre><code>&lt;AcceptButton&gt;Accept&lt;/AcceptButton&gt;</code></pre>
            <p>Typically styled as a success/confirmation action.</p>

            <h3>CancelButton</h3>
            <pre><code>&lt;CancelButton&gt;Cancel&lt;/CancelButton&gt;</code></pre>
            <p>A neutral action to dismiss or cancel an operation.</p>

            <h3>CloseButton</h3>
            <pre><code>&lt;CloseButton /&gt;</code></pre>
            <p>Renders a close/dismiss button (usually an ✕ icon).</p>

            <h3>DeleteButton</h3>
            <pre><code>&lt;DeleteButton&gt;Delete&lt;/DeleteButton&gt;</code></pre>
            <p>A destructive action styled as a warning/danger button.</p>

            <h3>DestructiveButton</h3>
            <pre><code>&lt;DestructiveButton&gt;Remove All&lt;/DestructiveButton&gt;</code></pre>
            <p>A generic destructive action with high-visibility warning styling.</p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard>
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="shared-parameters">Shared Parameters</h2>

            <p>
                All semantic buttons inherit from <code>Button</code> and share the
                same parameters: <code>Class</code>, <code>Specialization</code>,
                <code>Style</code>, <code>Tooltip</code>, and <code>ChildContent</code>.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="bootstrap">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="semantic-buttons-bootstrap">Bootstrap 5 Semantic Buttons</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">Bootstrap 5 Semantic Buttons</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                In Bootstrap 5, each semantic button alias resolves to the appropriate Bootstrap
                variant class. AcceptButton maps to btn-success, CancelButton maps to btn-secondary,
                DeleteButton and DestructiveButton map to btn-danger, and CloseButton maps to
                Bootstrap's btn-close. These mappings are defined in the VanillaBootstrap5 design
                system and apply automatically without any manual class configuration.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="daisyui">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="semantic-buttons-daisyui">DaisyUI Semantic Buttons</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">DaisyUI Semantic Buttons</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                In DaisyUI, semantic button aliases map to DaisyUI's semantic color tokens.
                AcceptButton uses btn-success, CancelButton uses btn-neutral, DeleteButton and
                DestructiveButton use btn-error. These tokens are theme-aware, meaning their
                visual appearance adapts when you switch DaisyUI themes. CloseButton renders
                with a minimal btn-ghost style suitable for inline dismiss controls.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="basecoat">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="semantic-buttons-basecoat">Basecoat Semantic Buttons</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">Basecoat Semantic Buttons</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                In Basecoat, semantic button aliases are composed from Tailwind utility classes
                that reflect the intent of each action. AcceptButton uses green-toned utilities,
                CancelButton uses neutral utilities, and DeleteButton and DestructiveButton use
                red-toned utilities. Because Basecoat is utility-first, you can further refine
                the appearance of any semantic button through the Class or Specialization parameters.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

</main>

<TableOfContents Items="@([
    new TocItem("semantic-buttons", "Semantic Buttons"),
    new TocItem("overview", "Overview", 2),
    new TocItem("shared-parameters", "Shared Parameters", 2),
    new TocItem("semantic-buttons-bootstrap", "Bootstrap 5 Semantic Buttons", 2),
    new TocItem("semantic-buttons-daisyui", "DaisyUI Semantic Buttons", 2),
    new TocItem("semantic-buttons-basecoat", "Basecoat Semantic Buttons", 2)
])" />

</div>
